gmd:abstract.gco:CharacterString: Ayres Associates provided NCWRPC with digital orthoimagery services in 2015 as part of WROC. The coverage area included 41 counties in Wisconsin and was flown in spring 2014 and spring 2015 under leaf-off conditions. The 4-band (RGB-NIR) aerial imagery was collected using either a Leica Geosystems ADS 100 or Microsoft Vexcel UltraCam Eagle sensor outfitted in a fixed-wing aircraft with onboard GPS/IMU systems and gyro-stabilized mounts. The native resolution aerial imagery was acquired to support 6-inch and 12-inch ground sample distance (GSD) specifications. Resultant orthoimagery was rectified to new DEMs created from the acquired imagery and existing LiDAR where available. Orthoimagery was delivered in DOQQ GeoTIFF format by county. The re-sampled 4-band, 18-inch pixel DOQQ orthoimagery meets or exceeds +/- 14.4 foot horizontal accuracy at 95% confidence level according to ASPRS standards. Supplemental Information: The Wisconsin Regional Orthophotography Consortium (WROC) is a multi-entity group led by regional planning commissions (RPCs) and WROC representatives from Ayres Associates. The goal of the consortium is to build and sustain a multi-participant program to acquire digital orthoimagery and elevation data throughout Wisconsin. Orthoimagery was collected to provide consistent deliverable products and accuracy standards for each of the participating entities.

gmd:purpose.gco:CharacterString: Ayres Associates was contracted through the NCWRPC for the creation of 18-inch pixel DOQQ's from the native resolution digital orthophotography produced under the Wisconsin Regional Orthophotography Consortium (WROC) in 2014-15. This project established DOQQ's for state and federal partners using all member data acquired under the Consortium. Please refer to http://www.ncwrpc.org/WROC2015/ for more information on the Consortium.

gmd:supplementalInformation.gco:CharacterString: WROC imagery was flown in the spring of 2015, resulting in a "leaf-off" aerial photo product. The entire state of Wisconsin is NOT included in the WROC 2015 flight. County mosaics (.sid) are available for download via WisconsinView. For coverage information, please see: http://www.sco.wisc.edu/images/stories/publications/2016/SCO_Wisconsin_Orthophotography_Jan_2016.pdf For more information: http://www.ncwrpc.org/WROC/Delivery_Specs.pdf 2015

gmd:measureDescription.gco:CharacterString: Images were color corrected to match adjacent flight lines. The resulting imagery was globally tilted in terms of contrast and color to form a radiometrically consistent orthophoto mosaic.
These data cover the entirety of the 2014-15 WROC NCWRPC Orthophotography Initiative.

gmd:description.gco:CharacterString: Ground control consisted of photo identifiable surveyed points. The imagery was collected using either a Leica Geosystems ADS 100 or Microsoft Vexcel UltraCam Eagle at 14.5 or 29cm GSD. Image quality was verified during the post flight review phase. Factors considered during this review included but were not limited to the presence of cloud cover, contrails, light conditions and sun flare. A rigorous Aerotriangulation process was performed and supplemented by the photo ID survey points. The triangulated strips were rectified with new DEMs created from the acquired imagery and existing LiDAR where available. The imagery was mosaicked using manual seamlines generation and tone/color balanced to a county-wide consistency. 4-band tiles were extracted from the mosaic and each individual tile was reviewed for artifacts and anomalies and adjusted as part of quality control procedures. The images were reviewed for rectification problems such as bridge displacements and seamline issues caused by the underlying digital elevation model. When necessary, local corrections to the imagery were performed to minimize such effects.
